Everyone has given you some great advice. IMHO, here are some basics that
you need:

1. A job
2. A real address
3. A real bank account (checking account)
4. A token savings account with a bank or credit union
5. A secured credit card with a $300 limit.

then, move up to:

6. A non-secured credit card
7. Store credit cards, like Best Buy or Circuit City or JC Penney

Now, all you need to do is to stay &quot;current&quot;....that is, pay your bills on
time.

Before you know it, you'll have credit deals mailed to you without even
asking.

Right now, IMHO, the &quot;key&quot; is to &quot;stay current&quot;, that is, never pay late. I
try to pay my bills within 48 hours of receiving them.

Also, I started with nothing but a $300 secured card. Now, that company has
elevated me to a $2,400 unsecured card.

It takes time and patience. Check out newsgroups like misc.consumers
(that's right here) and misc.legal, you'll see that the lenders, more than
ever, want to give you all the credit you want, but only if you have a good
record of paying them.

